#### Differentiating the Computer and Paper Tests
Background context: The ASVAB can be taken in two versions—computerized (CAT-ASVAB) or paper-and-pencil (P&P). High school students typically take the P&P version, while military applicants may have a choice between both formats. Additionally, there is an internet-delivered Computerized Adaptive Test (PiCAT) that some individuals might take on their own time.

:p What are the main differences between the computerized and paper versions of the ASVAB?
??x
The main differences lie in the format and convenience. The computerized version allows for adaptive testing, where questions adjust based on your answers to maximize accuracy and efficiency. It also provides real-time results. In contrast, the paper version is static and requires more time to grade. 
```java
// Pseudocode for a simple test flow
if (testFormat == "computerized") {
    // Use adaptive testing logic
} else if (testFormat == "paper") {
    // Standard paper-based testing process
}
```
x??

#### Computerized ASVAB vs. Paper ASVAB in Military Context
Background context: For military enlistment, the ASVAB can be taken either as a computerized version or on paper-and-pencil. The computerized version (CAT-ASVAB) is more common due to its efficiency and ability to provide immediate results. Paper tests are limited to specific locations such as Military Entrance Test (MET) sites.

:p What versions of the ASVAB can military recruits take, and where might they be offered?
??x
Military recruits can take either a computerized version or a paper-and-pencil version of the ASVAB. The computerized version (CAT-ASVAB) is typically administered at Military Entrance Processing Stations (MEPS), which offer one-stop shopping for testing, medical examinations, and enlistment. Paper versions are only available at MET sites that are not easily accessible to MEPS.

```java
// Pseudocode for scheduling an ASVAB test session
if (recruitPreference == "computerized") {
    scheduleTestAtMEPS();
} else if (recruitPreference == "paper") {
    findClosestMETSite();
}
```
